RETO MEIER: Hello, and welcome
to a very special episode of

00:00:08.300 --> 00:00:09.480
The App Clinic.

00:00:09.480 --> 00:00:11.890
IAN NI-LEWIS: Today, we're
broadcasting our pilot episode

00:00:11.890 --> 00:00:15.340
of the GDG App Clinic, starring
talented developers

00:00:15.340 --> 00:00:17.040
from Prague.

00:00:17.040 --> 00:00:20.280
RETO MEIER: We thought it might
be fun to visit Prague--

00:00:20.280 --> 00:00:21.770
IAN NI-LEWIS: But we couldn't
get the budget.

00:00:21.770 --> 00:00:24.540
So instead, we invited one
of the Prague GDGs

00:00:24.540 --> 00:00:25.850
to join us via Hangout.

00:00:25.850 --> 00:00:27.360
RETO MEIER: We gave each
developer a few minutes to

00:00:27.360 --> 00:00:29.970
introduce their app, and it was
our turn to give candid

00:00:29.970 --> 00:00:32.910
feedback on how to make their
good apps even better.

00:00:32.910 --> 00:00:35.560
IAN NI-LEWIS: We're hoping to
repeat this with GDGs all over

00:00:35.560 --> 00:00:37.670
the world, so let us
know if you want to

00:00:37.670 --> 00:00:39.070
be part of the magic.

00:00:39.070 --> 00:00:41.110
But be warned, Czech
developers know

00:00:41.110 --> 00:00:42.130
what they're doing.

00:00:42.130 --> 00:00:44.970
RETO MEIER: So without further
ado, welcome to the GDG App

00:00:44.970 --> 00:00:46.220
Clinic, Prague.

00:00:50.310 --> 00:00:54.860
RETO MEIER: Thank you very much
for inviting us to your

00:00:54.860 --> 00:00:56.820
GDG in Prague.

00:00:56.820 --> 00:00:57.980
I'm a big fan of Prague.

00:00:57.980 --> 00:01:00.610
I love the city-- been there a
few times, not just for Google

00:01:00.610 --> 00:01:03.020
Developer days, but
for fun as well.

00:01:03.020 --> 00:01:05.209
And one of the things which I
always come away from whenever

00:01:05.209 --> 00:01:08.250
I go to Prague is how great
the developers are.

00:01:08.250 --> 00:01:10.760
It's one of the big reasons why
Google has a big interest

00:01:10.760 --> 00:01:14.330
in what happens in Prague, so we
are really honored to have

00:01:14.330 --> 00:01:16.435
this opportunity to take a look
at some of the apps that

00:01:16.435 --> 00:01:18.690
you guys have put together,
hopefully give you some

00:01:18.690 --> 00:01:22.090
feedback, and just basically
hear from you guys as well as

00:01:22.090 --> 00:01:25.130
to what you've been working
on and what

00:01:25.130 --> 00:01:26.940
inspires you about Android.

00:01:26.940 --> 00:01:29.250
IAN NI-LEWIS: And I've been to
Prague once on the way to

00:01:29.250 --> 00:01:30.190
[INAUDIBLE].

00:01:30.190 --> 00:01:32.300
That's pretty much it.

00:01:32.300 --> 00:01:34.220
MALE SPEAKER: [LAUGHS]

00:01:34.220 --> 00:01:35.660
Great.

00:01:35.660 --> 00:01:39.050
OK, so let's invite
our first speaker.

00:01:39.050 --> 00:01:40.120
MALE SPEAKER: Hi, guys.

00:01:40.120 --> 00:01:41.620
Nice to meet you.

00:01:41.620 --> 00:01:44.840
It's a pleasure to kick off
this fantastic event, so I

00:01:44.840 --> 00:01:48.110
hope we get some
great feedback.

00:01:48.110 --> 00:01:50.700
So our application is
called Big Launcher.

00:01:50.700 --> 00:01:55.710
As the name suggests, it's a
launcher suitable for seniors,

00:01:55.710 --> 00:01:58.840
for people who are visually
impaired, and

00:01:58.840 --> 00:02:01.460
for disabled people.

00:02:01.460 --> 00:02:06.170
It uses big icons and large
text for all the basic

00:02:06.170 --> 00:02:10.150
functions of the phone,
including contacts, including

00:02:10.150 --> 00:02:15.050
messaging, including call log,
and also it can launch

00:02:15.050 --> 00:02:16.760
applications.

00:02:16.760 --> 00:02:18.930
RETO MEIER: So this is Big
Launcher up on our giant,

00:02:18.930 --> 00:02:23.310
giant phone, and it, exactly
as the developer said--

00:02:23.310 --> 00:02:25.860
oh, by the way, make sure you
guys introduce yourselves when

00:02:25.860 --> 00:02:28.010
you get started as well, so
we know what to call you.

00:02:28.010 --> 00:02:30.050
What is your name, sir?

00:02:30.050 --> 00:02:30.936
MALE SPEAKER: [INAUDIBLE].

00:02:30.936 --> 00:02:31.380
RETO MEIER: [INAUDIBLE].

00:02:31.380 --> 00:02:31.760
All right.

00:02:31.760 --> 00:02:32.140
Perfect.

00:02:32.140 --> 00:02:33.450
IAN NI-LEWIS: That's
a great name.

00:02:33.450 --> 00:02:34.160
RETO MEIER: It is
a great name.

00:02:34.160 --> 00:02:36.320
I feel like we're not going to
be able to pronounce any of

00:02:36.320 --> 00:02:39.660
the names today, so we've
started about as simple as

00:02:39.660 --> 00:02:40.760
it's going to get, and
it's going to go

00:02:40.760 --> 00:02:42.120
downhill from here.

00:02:42.120 --> 00:02:43.570
Nonetheless, [INAUDIBLE] has
done a great job here.

00:02:43.570 --> 00:02:46.820
You can see Big Launcher is
exactly what it says it is.

00:02:46.820 --> 00:02:50.550
It's a replacement
launch screen.

00:02:50.550 --> 00:02:51.920
And it is exactly that.

00:02:51.920 --> 00:02:55.390
So it's nice big buttons, bright
icons, really easy to

00:02:55.390 --> 00:02:56.870
see what's going on.

00:02:56.870 --> 00:02:58.750
One of the things that I
did find was during the

00:02:58.750 --> 00:03:01.570
configuration process, there's
a setup wizard that you go

00:03:01.570 --> 00:03:07.350
through, and as part of that
process, it feels like that's

00:03:07.350 --> 00:03:08.760
actually quite complex.

00:03:08.760 --> 00:03:10.470
So it's almost as though it's
an app that you're going to

00:03:10.470 --> 00:03:14.145
want to set up for someone else,
rather than have the

00:03:14.145 --> 00:03:17.340
visually impaired older person
set it up themselves.

00:03:17.340 --> 00:03:19.630
IAN NI-LEWIS: That's kind of
the impression that I got.

00:03:19.630 --> 00:03:22.010
I don't know how else you could
do it, really, because

00:03:22.010 --> 00:03:26.610
obviously, you're going to have
some steps where you have

00:03:26.610 --> 00:03:28.730
to dig into this stuff
that's in the phone

00:03:28.730 --> 00:03:31.010
already, you know?

00:03:31.010 --> 00:03:33.270
At least just to set it up
as the default launcher.

00:03:33.270 --> 00:03:34.830
RETO MEIER: So that's something
that you may want to

00:03:34.830 --> 00:03:37.810
consider is what is the target
audience for that

00:03:37.810 --> 00:03:39.060
phase of the app?

00:03:39.060 --> 00:03:42.850
So if that's more for your
expert user, so yourself or

00:03:42.850 --> 00:03:44.780
whoever is setting up a phone
for your parent or

00:03:44.780 --> 00:03:47.880
grandparent, then you may want
to try and make that a little

00:03:47.880 --> 00:03:51.510
bit more familiar to the
standard phone UI, and then

00:03:51.510 --> 00:03:55.330
keep the large screen simplified
stuff for the final

00:03:55.330 --> 00:03:56.370
home screen itself.

00:03:56.370 --> 00:03:59.140
There's is also a couple of tips
about the wizard setup

00:03:59.140 --> 00:04:00.400
process itself.

00:04:00.400 --> 00:04:03.940
It doesn't quite follow a
standard wizard type UI.

00:04:03.940 --> 00:04:06.910
So in a normal wizard, I want
to be able to go to navigate

00:04:06.910 --> 00:04:09.910
backwards and forwards until
I'm complete, and I noticed

00:04:09.910 --> 00:04:11.320
that when I was doing
this setup, I

00:04:11.320 --> 00:04:12.520
had to simply progress.

00:04:12.520 --> 00:04:14.290
It was just sort of a series
of questions that

00:04:14.290 --> 00:04:15.760
got put up on screen.

00:04:15.760 --> 00:04:17.630
I answered them, I chose
my default, whatever

00:04:17.630 --> 00:04:19.040
else, and moved on.

00:04:19.040 --> 00:04:22.850
Now, if the idea here is that it
is for the older person to

00:04:22.850 --> 00:04:25.880
use themselves, then that kind
of makes a lot of sense.

00:04:25.880 --> 00:04:27.950
You don't want to have to put
too many buttons on screen,

00:04:27.950 --> 00:04:29.330
too much confusing navigation.

00:04:29.330 --> 00:04:31.690
Just one big question,
make a decision, move

00:04:31.690 --> 00:04:33.230
on to the next part.

00:04:33.230 --> 00:04:35.160
But I'm not sure that
it quite worked.

00:04:35.160 --> 00:04:37.980
It was a little bit too complex
for that use case, a

00:04:37.980 --> 00:04:42.170
little bit too basic for
the more expert user.

00:04:42.170 --> 00:04:44.030
One of the things that I noticed
through that wizard

00:04:44.030 --> 00:04:46.010
process as well was that
you're able to select a

00:04:46.010 --> 00:04:48.360
language, or go by default.

00:04:48.360 --> 00:04:51.040
Now, I was a little confused by
that, because the phone is

00:04:51.040 --> 00:04:52.750
obviously going to have
a language set.

00:04:52.750 --> 00:04:54.910
You can have the different
resource folders to make sure

00:04:54.910 --> 00:04:56.590
the correct assets are loaded.

00:04:56.590 --> 00:04:59.080
Was there a particular reason
why you wanted to allow people

00:04:59.080 --> 00:05:00.820
to select a language
independent

00:05:00.820 --> 00:05:03.350
of the phone itself?

00:05:03.350 --> 00:05:04.960
MALE SPEAKER: Yeah,
there's a reason.

00:05:04.960 --> 00:05:11.100
Because we feel that's some
of the users can have the

00:05:11.100 --> 00:05:17.700
different language set in the
system settings, but and they

00:05:17.700 --> 00:05:21.650
want to use a different language
in Launcher itself.

00:05:21.650 --> 00:05:24.880
For example, some immigrants
or people like that.

00:05:24.880 --> 00:05:26.040
So that's why.

00:05:26.040 --> 00:05:26.640
IAN NI-LEWIS: That's true.

00:05:26.640 --> 00:05:28.440
I think if I were setting
up this phone for my

00:05:28.440 --> 00:05:31.420
mother-in-law, Chinese, I think
that I would want the

00:05:31.420 --> 00:05:33.780
setup to be in English, but she,
of course, would want to

00:05:33.780 --> 00:05:34.410
see it in Chinese.

00:05:34.410 --> 00:05:35.220
RETO MEIER: Would want to have
the launcher in Chinese.

00:05:35.220 --> 00:05:35.880
That makes a lot of sense.

00:05:35.880 --> 00:05:36.440
All right.

00:05:36.440 --> 00:05:39.370
I'm learning stuff myself.

00:05:39.370 --> 00:05:42.390
So when I'm actually using the
app-- so you can see here that

00:05:42.390 --> 00:05:45.160
the buttons are responsive,
which is nice.

00:05:45.160 --> 00:05:47.350
Whenever you're building custom
buttons, custom UI,

00:05:47.350 --> 00:05:50.130
it's really important to make
sure that they behave the same

00:05:50.130 --> 00:05:52.520
way that standard Android
buttons work.

00:05:52.520 --> 00:05:54.340
And so you need to have some
sort of feedback when you're

00:05:54.340 --> 00:05:55.490
pressing things.

00:05:55.490 --> 00:05:58.560
What I did notice, which I
would be interested to

00:05:58.560 --> 00:06:01.520
understand better, is generally,
for stuff like

00:06:01.520 --> 00:06:04.460
this, it might be useful to
have a long press, which

00:06:04.460 --> 00:06:07.340
triggers the accessibility by
default on the Jelly Bean

00:06:07.340 --> 00:06:08.070
[INAUDIBLE] phones.

00:06:08.070 --> 00:06:11.322
So the same way where on action
bar items, when you

00:06:11.322 --> 00:06:14.902
press it, it displays
help [INAUDIBLE]

00:06:14.902 --> 00:06:15.890
explaining what it is.

00:06:15.890 --> 00:06:16.400
That actually--

00:06:16.400 --> 00:06:17.230
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:06:17.230 --> 00:06:18.080
IAN NI-LEWIS: He actually
mentioned that though.

00:06:18.080 --> 00:06:23.400
He said that he felt like the
long press was unfriendly to

00:06:23.400 --> 00:06:24.680
this type of user.

00:06:24.680 --> 00:06:25.130
RETO MEIER: Yeah.

00:06:25.130 --> 00:06:26.330
And it could be.

00:06:26.330 --> 00:06:30.290
So how does one trigger the
accessibility talk back

00:06:30.290 --> 00:06:32.800
functions of the phone, then?

00:06:32.800 --> 00:06:36.570
MALE SPEAKER: Well, there
are two things.

00:06:36.570 --> 00:06:46.730
The first is that senior
people got problems to

00:06:46.730 --> 00:06:50.390
distinguish between long
press and short press.

00:06:50.390 --> 00:06:53.450
So we wanted to get
rid of that.

00:06:53.450 --> 00:06:58.470
And then, during the
development, we got to this

00:06:58.470 --> 00:07:06.580
idea, or the possibility to
use a long press for some

00:07:06.580 --> 00:07:07.600
other function.

00:07:07.600 --> 00:07:12.330
So you can turn on in the
accessibility options that on

00:07:12.330 --> 00:07:20.460
long press, the Big Launcher
reads the activated item.

00:07:20.460 --> 00:07:25.990
This is useful for older phones
with previous versions

00:07:25.990 --> 00:07:31.660
of Android, which doesn't have
the explore by touch function,

00:07:31.660 --> 00:07:40.690
so even on these older phones,
people can use this read by

00:07:40.690 --> 00:07:44.830
touch or read by long press
function developed by us, and

00:07:44.830 --> 00:07:50.420
they can be, for example,
reminded of

00:07:50.420 --> 00:07:53.190
what this icon does.

00:07:53.190 --> 00:07:57.550
So when you create a shortcut
for some application, you see

00:07:57.550 --> 00:08:01.710
only the icon, but when you
long press on it, the

00:08:01.710 --> 00:08:04.720
description of this icon
is red, so you'll

00:08:04.720 --> 00:08:06.280
remember what it does.

00:08:06.280 --> 00:08:07.040
RETO MEIER: Very nice.

00:08:07.040 --> 00:08:07.820
Very nice.

00:08:07.820 --> 00:08:10.550
So I mean, overall, there's not
a huge amount of feedback

00:08:10.550 --> 00:08:12.860
that we can give, apart from
getting a little bit nitpicky.

00:08:12.860 --> 00:08:17.260
I think that the padding around
the time and date on

00:08:17.260 --> 00:08:20.090
the top here is a little
bit narrow.

00:08:20.090 --> 00:08:22.610
You probably want to indent that
a little bit more to make

00:08:22.610 --> 00:08:25.100
it feel a little bit
more balanced.

00:08:25.100 --> 00:08:26.950
But really, a lot of the
feedback is going to be that

00:08:26.950 --> 00:08:29.020
kind of nitpicky stuff, so we're
going to make sure that

00:08:29.020 --> 00:08:30.750
we include that in an
email, and send

00:08:30.750 --> 00:08:31.960
you off those details.

00:08:31.960 --> 00:08:33.919
We're going to get Roman,
Nick, and Adam from the

00:08:33.919 --> 00:08:36.510
Android Design In Action Team
as well to provide a little

00:08:36.510 --> 00:08:40.015
bit of extra feedback on UI
elements to this app, and all

00:08:40.015 --> 00:08:42.770
the ones we look at today,
rather than spend too much

00:08:42.770 --> 00:08:45.630
time complaining about two
pixels being missing from a

00:08:45.630 --> 00:08:47.370
particular part of the UI.

00:08:47.370 --> 00:08:50.430
IAN NI-LEWIS: Although I did
have one comment on the clock.

00:08:50.430 --> 00:08:53.440
I was little surprised, because
I've always been told

00:08:53.440 --> 00:08:59.540
that digital clocks were less
accessible, and that older

00:08:59.540 --> 00:09:01.120
people would prefer
analog clocks.

00:09:01.120 --> 00:09:02.870
But you used a digital
clock here.

00:09:02.870 --> 00:09:06.760
I'm wondering, was that
a conscious decision?

00:09:06.760 --> 00:09:10.360
MALE SPEAKER: Well, it's, again,
because of the support

00:09:10.360 --> 00:09:14.730
of low res devices and older
phones, because you don't have

00:09:14.730 --> 00:09:22.890
too much space on phones
with 240 by 320.

00:09:22.890 --> 00:09:25.670
IAN NI-LEWIS: Good point.

00:09:25.670 --> 00:09:28.480
MALE SPEAKER: We also, if you
turn on the option in

00:09:28.480 --> 00:09:32.920
preferences, there's also
enlarge, better indicator, and

00:09:32.920 --> 00:09:37.020
mobile signal indicator, and we
are really getting low on

00:09:37.020 --> 00:09:37.803
space there.

00:09:37.803 --> 00:09:39.350
RETO MEIER: No, that's
a really good point.

00:09:39.350 --> 00:09:40.420
IAN NI-LEWIS: No, that
makes sense.

00:09:40.420 --> 00:09:42.830
RETO MEIER: So a couple of very
quick last minute points.

00:09:42.830 --> 00:09:45.990
So it does have an old school
venue button, which does

00:09:45.990 --> 00:09:52.190
display a custom, more easily
pressable menu, I suppose.

00:09:52.190 --> 00:09:53.910
I'd like to say, I understand
why you've got this,

00:09:53.910 --> 00:09:55.610
particularly for backwards
compatible

00:09:55.610 --> 00:09:57.370
support for older devices.

00:09:57.370 --> 00:10:00.000
I did note that you still have
the Menu button, and it is a

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:02.080
little more shameful
in the wizard.

00:10:02.080 --> 00:10:04.610
There's no need to have
it available there.

00:10:04.610 --> 00:10:08.680
And here, I would think about
having a default mechanism on

00:10:08.680 --> 00:10:11.000
newer versions of the
device which get rid

00:10:11.000 --> 00:10:11.800
of that menu button.

00:10:11.800 --> 00:10:13.900
So I know that there is a
setting within the setup

00:10:13.900 --> 00:10:17.720
wizard which lets you optionally
choose to have

00:10:17.720 --> 00:10:20.170
preferences show up within
the UI itself.

00:10:20.170 --> 00:10:22.450
I'd consider defaulting that
to on and hiding that menu

00:10:22.450 --> 00:10:23.300
button away.

00:10:23.300 --> 00:10:26.420
It just will make the app look
more polished on newer

00:10:26.420 --> 00:10:29.350
devices-- make people feel
like it's a more polished

00:10:29.350 --> 00:10:30.930
final product.

00:10:30.930 --> 00:10:32.820
And the other piece of
suggestion I would have as

00:10:32.820 --> 00:10:35.000
well, particularly around-- it
seems like you're having to

00:10:35.000 --> 00:10:38.080
make a lot of UI compromises
and choices based on what

00:10:38.080 --> 00:10:40.820
makes it easier to use
by older people.

00:10:40.820 --> 00:10:43.120
I would, if you're not already,
strongly suggest that

00:10:43.120 --> 00:10:46.220
you make sure to use a lot of
analytics to find out exactly

00:10:46.220 --> 00:10:47.380
what people are doing.

00:10:47.380 --> 00:10:48.610
Are they long processing?

00:10:48.610 --> 00:10:49.960
Are they then hitting back?

00:10:49.960 --> 00:10:51.400
What are the behaviors?

00:10:51.400 --> 00:10:52.080
What are the choices?

00:10:52.080 --> 00:10:55.630
What are the outcomes of some
of those compromises?

00:10:55.630 --> 00:10:59.470
MALE SPEAKER: We did lots of
testing with the UI itself,

00:10:59.470 --> 00:11:06.245
but currently, we don't include
any analytics in the

00:11:06.245 --> 00:11:11.780
app, because again, it's
about the target group.

00:11:11.780 --> 00:11:16.090
We suppose that lots of seniors
don't have data tariff

00:11:16.090 --> 00:11:21.590
or mobile data at all, so we've
created this from the

00:11:21.590 --> 00:11:26.270
beginning to be a completely
offline application.

00:11:26.270 --> 00:11:26.550
RETO MEIER: Great.

00:11:26.550 --> 00:11:28.035
Well, I can't argue with that.

00:11:28.035 --> 00:11:29.310
It sounds like you've
thought it through.

00:11:29.310 --> 00:11:30.910
So nicely done.

00:11:30.910 --> 00:11:31.930
That's the thing.

00:11:31.930 --> 00:11:34.240
We could go on praising it,
but that doesn't seem--

00:11:34.240 --> 00:11:35.890
IAN NI-LEWIS: No,
it looks great.

00:11:35.890 --> 00:11:39.310
Well, actually, I've always got
one last thing, but you've

00:11:39.310 --> 00:11:42.390
got a really good point
that you don't want to

00:11:42.390 --> 00:11:43.280
use the data tariff.

00:11:43.280 --> 00:11:46.440
But have you considered maybe
doing analytics anyway and

00:11:46.440 --> 00:11:49.000
just storing it to persistent
storage?

00:11:49.000 --> 00:11:52.120
Because I feel like, especially
in the scenario

00:11:52.120 --> 00:11:56.400
where you have a caregiver
