00:14:57.160 --> 00:14:58.680
for the search button.

00:14:58.680 --> 00:15:02.930
I sort of expected it to be up
at the top, and instead, it

00:15:02.930 --> 00:15:03.560
was up at the bottom.

00:15:03.560 --> 00:15:05.850
Now, it's a perfect icon--

00:15:05.850 --> 00:15:07.740
search with a little plus?

00:15:07.740 --> 00:15:09.420
Like, oh, that's how
I add a stock.

00:15:09.420 --> 00:15:12.180
No worries there as soon
as I found it.

00:15:12.180 --> 00:15:15.450
It just took a little while to
find it, because it wasn't in

00:15:15.450 --> 00:15:16.650
the place I expected
on the action bar.

00:15:16.650 --> 00:15:17.570
RETO MEIER: Feels like it
should be in action.

00:15:17.570 --> 00:15:19.980
So that may be one piece of
feedback is to extend that

00:15:19.980 --> 00:15:22.415
bottom part out, move the
button up to the top.

00:15:22.415 --> 00:15:22.900
IAN NI-LEWIS: Yeah.

00:15:22.900 --> 00:15:27.500
We also usually say don't
put a refresh button.

00:15:27.500 --> 00:15:29.660
RETO MEIER: Yeah,
it's possible.

00:15:29.660 --> 00:15:32.930
I had a little bit of a look to
see how the refresh worked,

00:15:32.930 --> 00:15:36.230
and it seems that within
preferences, you're able to

00:15:36.230 --> 00:15:39.022
select your refresh frequency.

00:15:39.022 --> 00:15:40.512
So whenever I see that
sort of thing, I get

00:15:40.512 --> 00:15:42.130
a little bit nervous.

00:15:42.130 --> 00:15:48.700
So I feel like I need to ask how
you doing your refreshes.

00:15:48.700 --> 00:15:52.152
TOMAS VONDRACEK: I
beg your pardon?

00:15:52.152 --> 00:15:54.400
IAN NI-LEWIS: Yeah, sorry.

00:15:54.400 --> 00:15:59.280
How are you doing
your refreshing?

00:15:59.280 --> 00:16:03.520
TOMAS VONDRACEK: Well, the
application starts an alarm in

00:16:03.520 --> 00:16:04.790
particular interval.

00:16:04.790 --> 00:16:08.220
It's not waking up alarm.

00:16:08.220 --> 00:16:12.770
RETO MEIER: So it's an inexact
repeating non-wake alarm?

00:16:12.770 --> 00:16:16.370
TOMAS VONDRACEK: Not repeating,
but I set alarm

00:16:16.370 --> 00:16:20.080
every time I need to schedule
next update.

00:16:20.080 --> 00:16:20.400
RETO MEIER: OK.

00:16:20.400 --> 00:16:22.370
So one of the things about
that-- if you're doing that

00:16:22.370 --> 00:16:25.000
yourself and it's not repeating,
then it's going to

00:16:25.000 --> 00:16:26.920
trigger it basically
the exact time.

00:16:26.920 --> 00:16:29.160
So you may want to consider
sitting an inexact repeating

00:16:29.160 --> 00:16:32.270
alarm, even if you then disable
the alarm each time

00:16:32.270 --> 00:16:33.770
and reset it.

00:16:33.770 --> 00:16:36.890
That will give the system a
little bit of leeway to time

00:16:36.890 --> 00:16:40.600
shift all the alarms from the
different apps, and make sure

00:16:40.600 --> 00:16:44.000
that they're not waking up the
cell radio within in a few

00:16:44.000 --> 00:16:46.180
seconds of each other and
keeping the radio hot and

00:16:46.180 --> 00:16:48.610
draining the battery
more quickly.

00:16:48.610 --> 00:16:51.080
If you want to take it even a
step further, given that you

00:16:51.080 --> 00:16:54.100
said you have a server where
you're remembering what

00:16:54.100 --> 00:16:55.810
people's stocks are--

00:16:55.810 --> 00:16:57.860
so if you wanted to be really,
really battery efficient,

00:16:57.860 --> 00:17:00.890
really, really awesome, you
would actually do all of the

00:17:00.890 --> 00:17:04.210
parsing of the stocks on your
server, and use Google Cloud

00:17:04.210 --> 00:17:08.010
messaging to tell each of the
devices which have those

00:17:08.010 --> 00:17:11.119
particular stocks listed that
it's time for a refresh.

00:17:11.119 --> 00:17:13.220
And in fact, because the stock
data is so small, you could

00:17:13.220 --> 00:17:15.290
probably bundle that
within the payload.

00:17:15.290 --> 00:17:17.290
So you wouldn't actually need
to do any refreshing at all.

00:17:17.290 --> 00:17:21.089
You can just tell the devices,
GOOG is up 10%, and have it

00:17:21.089 --> 00:17:21.730
update that way.

00:17:21.730 --> 00:17:23.940
TOMAS VONDRACEK: So it wouldn't
mind if there was a

00:17:23.940 --> 00:17:28.079
lot of push messages from server
to all those apps?

00:17:28.079 --> 00:17:32.400
RETO MEIER: No, we have social
media apps like Twitter

00:17:32.400 --> 00:17:37.080
clients and instant messaging
apps all use

00:17:37.080 --> 00:17:39.560
Google Cloud messaging.

00:17:39.560 --> 00:17:42.250
There's no quota, very
efficient, definitely,

00:17:42.250 --> 00:17:43.838
definitely the way to go.

00:17:43.838 --> 00:17:45.170
TOMAS VONDRACEK: OK.

00:17:45.170 --> 00:17:45.860
RETO MEIER: So that's something
to look at.

00:17:45.860 --> 00:17:48.270
I think that's probably the
biggest piece of feedback

00:17:48.270 --> 00:17:49.840
which is going to really
transform this app.

00:17:49.840 --> 00:17:52.180
It's going to reduce your
latency, it's going to

00:17:52.180 --> 00:17:54.290
increase your battery life,
it's going to let you hide

00:17:54.290 --> 00:17:55.510
away these refresh buttons.

00:17:55.510 --> 00:17:58.900
So I think that would be
a tremendous asset.

