MALE SPEAKER: Yeah.

00:44:06.300 --> 00:44:07.180
RETO MEIER: That's
really nice.

00:44:07.180 --> 00:44:07.800
I really like that.

00:44:07.800 --> 00:44:08.990
I like the visualness of it.

00:44:08.990 --> 00:44:11.080
Makes it much easier
to see at a glance.

00:44:11.080 --> 00:44:14.350
IAN NI-LEWIS: I like that it's
both color coded and--

00:44:14.350 --> 00:44:15.030
RETO MEIER: Yes, it's
a picture and a

00:44:15.030 --> 00:44:16.580
color, which is nice.

00:44:16.580 --> 00:44:18.490
But it does mean you're
duplicating data.

00:44:18.490 --> 00:44:20.290
So I don't need to
see the word sea

00:44:20.290 --> 00:44:21.270
next to the sea shell.

00:44:21.270 --> 00:44:24.050
Like, you should just train your
users so they understand

00:44:24.050 --> 00:44:24.980
that that's what that means.

00:44:24.980 --> 00:44:27.890
And certainly when you click
through to details, it's

00:44:27.890 --> 00:44:31.400
useful then to say what it is,
just so that they can learn

00:44:31.400 --> 00:44:33.210
what those different
icons mean.

00:44:33.210 --> 00:44:35.720
But on this main screen, I want
to see the name of the

00:44:35.720 --> 00:44:38.280
beach be bigger, basically.

00:44:38.280 --> 00:44:40.390
Make it easier to read,
easier to see.

00:44:40.390 --> 00:44:42.610
That's the main piece of
information that you're trying

00:44:42.610 --> 00:44:43.240
to pass on.

00:44:43.240 --> 00:44:44.850
IAN NI-LEWIS: Same with
the distance, I think.

00:44:44.850 --> 00:44:45.420
RETO MEIER: Exactly.

00:44:45.420 --> 00:44:48.240
IAN NI-LEWIS: Especially here,
where we've got some beaches

00:44:48.240 --> 00:44:49.870
that are relatively close,
and then some that

00:44:49.870 --> 00:44:50.880
are very far away.

00:44:50.880 --> 00:44:52.650
It would be useful to
have the distance

00:44:52.650 --> 00:44:53.750
a little more scannable.

00:44:53.750 --> 00:44:54.610
RETO MEIER: Absolutely.

00:44:54.610 --> 00:44:56.980
One other thing that you may
want to do-- so if I navigate

00:44:56.980 --> 00:45:00.120
in, I have the ability to
hit map or navigation.

00:45:00.120 --> 00:45:01.680
Really nice touch.

00:45:01.680 --> 00:45:05.290
I would consider adding the
navigation action to this main

00:45:05.290 --> 00:45:08.800
list view on the right hand
side, because if I was using

00:45:08.800 --> 00:45:11.000
the app, a lot of the time,
that's what I'm going to do.

00:45:11.000 --> 00:45:14.770
So if I'm driving upward down
the Pacific coast, and I want

00:45:14.770 --> 00:45:18.280
to watch the sun set at a beach,
I'm going to take a

00:45:18.280 --> 00:45:20.180
look at this, look for all of
the pink things, and the

00:45:20.180 --> 00:45:22.750
nearest one I find, I'm just
going to hit navigate to find

00:45:22.750 --> 00:45:24.530
out how to drive there.

00:45:24.530 --> 00:45:26.580
So again, this depends
on your use case.

00:45:26.580 --> 00:45:29.980
So this is a really good example
of why analytics can

00:45:29.980 --> 00:45:32.940
be useful, to find out, well,
what percentage of your users

00:45:32.940 --> 00:45:35.570
are going through here and
straight away clicking

00:45:35.570 --> 00:45:36.740
navigation?

00:45:36.740 --> 00:45:39.110
If that's a common use case,
then that's something you want

00:45:39.110 --> 00:45:40.000
to promote.

00:45:40.000 --> 00:45:41.850
And similarly, try to decide--

00:45:41.850 --> 00:45:44.520
and this is kind of good advice
for most developers--

00:45:44.520 --> 00:45:47.090
decide what do you want
your users to do?

00:45:47.090 --> 00:45:48.610
What are the main actions?

00:45:48.610 --> 00:45:50.030
What counts as success?

00:45:50.030 --> 00:45:52.540
So do you want them to go
through and read as many of

00:45:52.540 --> 00:45:56.660
these as possible, or add
photos, or use it to navigate?

00:45:56.660 --> 00:45:58.140
What are those primary
actions?

00:45:58.140 --> 00:46:02.222
And make that as simple as
possible for them to achieve.

00:46:02.222 --> 00:46:03.210
MALE SPEAKER: Great.

00:46:03.210 --> 00:46:07.770
As of now, we mostly want them
to add as much information as

00:46:07.770 --> 00:46:09.512
possible, upload photos.

00:46:09.512 --> 00:46:11.940
The navigation is
just a candy.

00:46:11.940 --> 00:46:13.660
RETO MEIER: Just nice to have?

00:46:13.660 --> 00:46:13.920
I get that.

00:46:13.920 --> 00:46:15.840
And so that's good advice.

00:46:15.840 --> 00:46:17.930
So then what you may want to do
is consider adding one of

00:46:17.930 --> 00:46:21.410
those actions to this main
screen so that you can say,

00:46:21.410 --> 00:46:22.540
oh, I'm at that beach.

00:46:22.540 --> 00:46:25.910
So you just open it up, you go
oh, the one at the top is

00:46:25.910 --> 00:46:28.620
where I'm at, and have the
button there to add photos

00:46:28.620 --> 00:46:30.180
directly from it.

00:46:30.180 --> 00:46:32.750
Obviously, that introduces a UI
challenge, and making it a

00:46:32.750 --> 00:46:34.430
little bit more cluttered.

00:46:34.430 --> 00:46:36.300
So you may only want to add that
button for the item at

00:46:36.300 --> 00:46:38.090
the very top of the list.

00:46:38.090 --> 00:46:39.440
But it's something
to consider.

00:46:39.440 --> 00:46:42.480
You want to reduce the number
of clicks between the user

00:46:42.480 --> 00:46:44.810
opening your app and performing
whatever action you

00:46:44.810 --> 00:46:46.430
want them to perform.

00:46:46.430 --> 00:46:48.870
So similarly, you've got
the ad here, which

00:46:48.870 --> 00:46:50.470
is for adding places.

00:46:50.470 --> 00:46:52.340
Obviously, that's the main thing
that you want them to

00:46:52.340 --> 00:46:54.570
do, to build up that
community.

00:46:54.570 --> 00:47:01.570
So that may be another example
of why it may make sense to

00:47:01.570 --> 00:47:02.820
have that at the top.

00:47:02.820 --> 00:47:04.430
Because when most people are
opening the app, they're

00:47:04.430 --> 00:47:07.170
expecting the main actions
to be up here.

00:47:07.170 --> 00:47:09.430
And so by not having it there,
it makes it a little bit less

00:47:09.430 --> 00:47:11.830
likely that they hit
that plus button.

00:47:11.830 --> 00:47:14.240
You may even want to go a step
further, and if that really is

00:47:14.240 --> 00:47:17.130
the most important thing for
the app, is to have a big

00:47:17.130 --> 00:47:19.880
button somewhere maybe above
the list view, which

00:47:19.880 --> 00:47:22.010
encourages them to do that
first and foremost.

00:47:22.010 --> 00:47:26.830
Now, I wouldn't always do that,
but you can tell how

00:47:26.830 --> 00:47:27.490
important that is.

00:47:27.490 --> 00:47:29.980
So in Prague, you've got
probably most of the important

00:47:29.980 --> 00:47:32.270
swimming places there,
strong community.

00:47:32.270 --> 00:47:33.130
It's less important.

00:47:33.130 --> 00:47:35.400
So definitely don't show
it to people in Prague.

00:47:35.400 --> 00:47:38.840
Here in California, most of the
things here are missing.

00:47:38.840 --> 00:47:40.730
And so I open this app and I go,
well, this isn't actually

00:47:40.730 --> 00:47:43.575
that useful to me, because
there's nowhere nearby.

00:47:43.575 --> 00:47:45.970
But if the first thing up at
the top of the screen was

00:47:45.970 --> 00:47:47.785
actually a button asking
me to add places,

00:47:47.785 --> 00:47:49.280
well, that I can do.

00:47:49.280 --> 00:47:52.075
I know a bunch of places around
here that I can add.

00:47:52.075 --> 00:47:52.740
MALE SPEAKER: That's
a great point.

00:47:52.740 --> 00:47:54.730
Well, do add them.

00:47:54.730 --> 00:47:55.250
RETO MEIER: I will.

00:47:55.250 --> 00:47:58.270
I will set that as an action
item for myself.

00:47:58.270 --> 00:48:00.812
But that's my point is that you
want to make it obvious to

00:48:00.812 --> 00:48:03.220
the user, what do you
want from me to do?

00:48:03.220 --> 00:48:05.030
And then I can decide whether
that's something that is

00:48:05.030 --> 00:48:07.350
useful and interesting for me.

00:48:07.350 --> 00:48:08.400
So maybe have a look.

00:48:08.400 --> 00:48:12.040
If there's nowhere within
100 kilometers, make

00:48:12.040 --> 00:48:12.960
that the main option.

00:48:12.960 --> 00:48:15.290
Just say, please help
grow our community.

00:48:15.290 --> 00:48:17.050
People love that
sort of thing.

00:48:17.050 --> 00:48:20.020
So that may be something
to consider.

00:48:20.020 --> 00:48:21.190
MALE SPEAKER: Good point.

00:48:21.190 --> 00:48:25.810
IAN NI-LEWIS: Now, for the ad
screen, this might just be me,

00:48:25.810 --> 00:48:30.330
but I really feel like you'd get
a better user experience,

00:48:30.330 --> 00:48:36.240
and possibly more additions if
the first thing was a map.

00:48:36.240 --> 00:48:42.810
Because you have this nice
positional thing, but what I

00:48:42.810 --> 00:48:46.810
really want to do is-- the first
thing is I wanted to

00:48:46.810 --> 00:48:51.290
point to it on a map, and then
fill in information.

00:48:51.290 --> 00:48:54.470
The problem with this screen is
that the very first thing I

00:48:54.470 --> 00:48:57.980
see is three or four
text boxes and

00:48:57.980 --> 00:48:59.920
the on screen keyboard.

00:48:59.920 --> 00:49:02.475
And that immediately says to
me, oh my god, I'm going to

00:49:02.475 --> 00:49:06.360
have to do a lot of typing, and
I'm not into right now.

00:49:06.360 --> 00:49:07.880
I think I'll just go and
do something else.

00:49:07.880 --> 00:49:08.720
RETO MEIER: Yeah, that's
a good point.

00:49:08.720 --> 00:49:10.600
Because this is what you
get straight away.

00:49:10.600 --> 00:49:13.220
All you see is the text, and
you're like, oh, I just wanted

00:49:13.220 --> 00:49:14.660
to-- thing.

00:49:14.660 --> 00:49:16.520
So what Ian's saying is
a really good point.

00:49:16.520 --> 00:49:19.100
If this was the very first
thing-- so as soon as you

00:49:19.100 --> 00:49:23.000
click in here, you see a map
with an icon next to a quarry

00:49:23.000 --> 00:49:25.710
or a lake that I'm in,
it's like, OK, great.

00:49:25.710 --> 00:49:28.000
So I click that, and then the
next thing I get is it asks me

00:49:28.000 --> 00:49:28.860
for a name and stuff.

00:49:28.860 --> 00:49:32.190
And hopefully, as much of this
is optional as possible, so

00:49:32.190 --> 00:49:35.300
that you can just say, yeah,
it's the Pacific Ocean.

00:49:35.300 --> 00:49:37.830
IAN NI-LEWIS: Do we still
have the Places API that

00:49:37.830 --> 00:49:39.030
they can look up?

00:49:39.030 --> 00:49:40.000
RETO MEIER: I think
we do, yeah.

00:49:40.000 --> 00:49:40.720
IAN NI-LEWIS: We used to
be able to do that.

00:49:40.720 --> 00:49:42.240
RETO MEIER: I think that there's
still an API from

00:49:42.240 --> 00:49:44.930
Google-- a Places API that
allows you to search for

00:49:44.930 --> 00:49:46.420
points of interest.

00:49:46.420 --> 00:49:49.410
You may be able to use something
like that to help

00:49:49.410 --> 00:49:50.580
make suggestions
for your users.

00:49:50.580 --> 00:49:52.200
IAN NI-LEWIS: Help auto fill.

00:49:52.200 --> 00:49:52.470
RETO MEIER: Yeah.

00:49:52.470 --> 00:49:54.460
I don't think you're able to use
the data itself, but you

00:49:54.460 --> 00:49:58.020
can use it as a way to suggest
places that people can then

00:49:58.020 --> 00:49:59.560
fill in the data themselves.

00:49:59.560 --> 00:50:01.970
But do check the API terms of
service, because I don't want

00:50:01.970 --> 00:50:03.220
to steer you in the
wrong direction.

00:50:03.220 --> 00:50:04.410
MALE SPEAKER: I'll
look into it.

00:50:04.410 --> 00:50:07.675
RETO MEIER: Otherwise, all
this is really nice.

00:50:07.675 --> 00:50:09.460
Are you sure you
want to cancel?

00:50:09.460 --> 00:50:12.080
Ah, so this is a really
interesting dialog.

00:50:12.080 --> 00:50:13.500
Do you really want to cancel?

00:50:13.500 --> 00:50:15.110
All inserted data
will be lost.

00:50:15.110 --> 00:50:18.941
And if I hit cancel,
it doesn't cancel.

00:50:18.941 --> 00:50:21.890
IAN NI-LEWIS: Because it's
cancelling a cancel.

00:50:21.890 --> 00:50:22.960
RETO MEIER: Be careful
with that.

00:50:22.960 --> 00:50:24.690
MALE SPEAKER: All right, we
got a bug right there.

00:50:24.690 --> 00:50:26.350
RETO MEIER: Yeah.

00:50:26.350 --> 00:50:28.330
So make sure that you're
getting that right.

00:50:28.330 --> 00:50:31.370
I always forget what the correct
button order is here.

00:50:31.370 --> 00:50:34.630
I think you've got it right, but
make sure that you've got

00:50:34.630 --> 00:50:36.600
the yes no in the right order.

00:50:36.600 --> 00:50:38.710
It's all detailed in
the style guide.

00:50:38.710 --> 00:50:41.310
IAN NI-LEWIS: And maybe stay and
leave would be better than

00:50:41.310 --> 00:50:43.900
cancel and leave in this
case, because--

00:50:43.900 --> 00:50:44.190
RETO MEIER: Yeah.

00:50:44.190 --> 00:50:46.840
You just want two objective
things which it's clear which

00:50:46.840 --> 00:50:48.730
button is going to make you go
away, and which button is

00:50:48.730 --> 00:50:51.860
going to make the go away
button go away.

00:50:51.860 --> 00:50:53.540
IAN NI-LEWIS: Also, I would
suggest not showing that

00:50:53.540 --> 00:50:56.550
dialog if the user hasn't
actually entered in any

00:50:56.550 --> 00:50:56.930
information.

00:50:56.930 --> 00:50:57.655
RETO MEIER: That's
a good point.

00:50:57.655 --> 00:51:01.310
If there's no data to lose, then
there's no reason not to

00:51:01.310 --> 00:51:02.880
just let them back out.

00:51:02.880 --> 00:51:05.490
IAN NI-LEWIS: And in point of
fact, unless that becomes

00:51:05.490 --> 00:51:11.020
non-editable later, the absolute
best user experience

00:51:11.020 --> 00:51:16.410
is, if I haven't entered any
data, leave without prompting.

00:51:16.410 --> 00:51:19.890
If I have entered data, save
that data and leave without

00:51:19.890 --> 00:51:23.040
prompting, and then allow me to
delete the data that I've

00:51:23.040 --> 00:51:27.170
entered if it turns out that
I didn't actually want it.

00:51:27.170 --> 00:51:31.050
And that covers the 90% use case
with the least amount of

00:51:31.050 --> 00:51:33.880
intrusive dialogs.

00:51:33.880 --> 00:51:37.220
RETO MEIER: Otherwise, all of
the details are reasonable.

00:51:37.220 --> 00:51:40.180
The only issue here I have is
you've got these custom

00:51:40.180 --> 00:51:42.760
colored buttons along
the bottom here.

00:51:42.760 --> 00:51:45.540
In this example, I'm not sure
that it does make sense.

00:51:45.540 --> 00:51:47.305
They just feel a
little garish.

00:51:47.305 --> 00:51:50.220
The colors are really strong,
particularly around defaults.

00:51:50.220 --> 00:51:53.640
This makes me think defaults may
do something really bad.

00:51:53.640 --> 00:51:56.920
Big, bright red button,
like, seriously red.

00:51:56.920 --> 00:51:57.990
I think that's 25500 red.

00:51:57.990 --> 00:51:58.130
IAN NI-LEWIS: I know.

00:51:58.130 --> 00:52:00.520
It's like composing in Gmail.

00:52:00.520 --> 00:52:01.380
That's dangerous.

00:52:01.380 --> 00:52:02.760
RETO MEIER: That's a big deal.

00:52:06.500 --> 00:52:08.980
If nothing else, it makes it
seem like these are the two

00:52:08.980 --> 00:52:12.750
most important things on the
screen, and that show is going

00:52:12.750 --> 00:52:15.190
to do something magical, whereas
all it's really going

00:52:15.190 --> 00:52:16.890
to do is apply my
filters, right?

00:52:16.890 --> 00:52:20.320
Which is perfectly appropriate,
but I don't think

00:52:20.320 --> 00:52:24.760
that it's necessary to have
them differently colored.

00:52:27.300 --> 00:52:28.210
Let's see.

00:52:28.210 --> 00:52:30.040
So-- oops.

00:52:30.040 --> 00:52:32.930
So this is one of the dangers of
having all of your actions

00:52:32.930 --> 00:52:34.470
right here at the bottom,
is it's really easy to

00:52:34.470 --> 00:52:36.860
accidentally click
the wrong thing.

00:52:36.860 --> 00:52:38.230
So I totally did that
on purpose to

00:52:38.230 --> 00:52:40.770
demonstrate that point.

00:52:40.770 --> 00:52:41.110
Search.

00:52:41.110 --> 00:52:43.490
It would be nice to have
search as inline--

00:52:43.490 --> 00:52:45.490
so an action bar search
rather than

00:52:45.490 --> 00:52:47.710
popping up its own screen.

00:52:47.710 --> 00:52:50.830
Particularly, that way you can
see what is already there

00:52:50.830 --> 00:52:53.940
before we start searching and
having auto complete in that

00:52:53.940 --> 00:52:54.950
would be nice as well.

00:52:54.950 --> 00:52:57.010
IAN NI-LEWIS: I actualy feel
that way about filters, too.

00:52:57.010 --> 00:52:59.830
I think it's a little harder
to do, but especially when

00:52:59.830 --> 00:53:03.250
