shows me all of the sea.

00:53:30.610 --> 00:53:33.880
So it applies that filter that
way, rather than having to go

00:53:33.880 --> 00:53:35.470
through the second screen.

00:53:35.470 --> 00:53:37.160
Again, I think that's something
you probably want to

00:53:37.160 --> 00:53:39.700
beta test with people to see
if that means that they get

00:53:39.700 --> 00:53:41.930
lost, and they don't know
how to go back.

00:53:41.930 --> 00:53:43.910
But something like that as a
way of being able to click

00:53:43.910 --> 00:53:46.570
here, get a list of all of the
lakes, and if I hit back, it

00:53:46.570 --> 00:53:49.000
takes me back to the main screen
that's unfiltered.

00:53:49.000 --> 00:53:50.165
I think that would be
really interesting.

00:53:50.165 --> 00:53:51.770
IAN NI-LEWIS: I would get
lost on the list.

00:53:51.770 --> 00:53:54.380
I might be OK with that
on the second screen.

00:53:54.380 --> 00:53:55.140
RETO MEIER: On the
second screen ?

00:53:55.140 --> 00:53:55.530
IAN NI-LEWIS: Yeah.

00:53:55.530 --> 00:53:55.670
RETO MEIER: Yeah.

00:53:55.670 --> 00:53:57.080
IAN NI-LEWIS: It's tough.

00:53:57.080 --> 00:53:58.530
RETO MEIER: It's interesting.

00:53:58.530 --> 00:54:00.785
Again, basically, what we're
trying to come up with here

00:54:00.785 --> 00:54:03.550
are ways to reduce the
number of clicks to

00:54:03.550 --> 00:54:05.420
implement any behavior.

